FT  09 JUL 92 / UK warships on Serbian sanctions alert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO BRITISH warships are standing by to take part in a naval operation that
European countries are considering launching to enforce trade sanctions
against Serbia and its ally, Montenegro.
Mr John Major, UK prime minister, said last night that the destroyer HMS
Nottingham was at sea in the Mediterranean. British officials later
disclosed that the frigate HMS Avenger was travelling to join her.
Both ships are expected to remain in the region until a firm decision is
made on any military action to prevent goods reaching Serbia and Montenegro.
Foreign ministers of the nine-nation Western European Union, meeting
tomorrow in Helsinki, are expected to discuss plans for naval operations to
check that sanctions are being observed.
They are also likely to discuss the need for armed protection of
humanitarian aid convoys to the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo.
The UN imposed economic sanctions against the two Yugoslav republics early
last month to put pressure on the Serbs to stop ethnic fighting in breakaway
republics that have declared independence from Yugoslavia.
Mr Major said in Munich after the Group of Seven summit that HMS Nottingham
would initially log ships going to Yugoslav ports.
'If it were to go further and there were to be stop and search, which
conceivably it could, that would require a further United Nations
resolution,' he said.
Mr Major stressed that there was no question of Britain putting ground
troops into Bosnia-Hercegovina.
Judy Dempsey adds from Helsinki: British businessmen who have temporarily
closed their offices or operations in Belgrade, the Serbian capital, said
sanctions-busting was common.
'Electronic goods and spare parts are coming across the Adriatic, into
Montenegro and up to Serbia,' one businessman said.
Another said that Albania was often used as a staging post. Goods were then
moved north into neighbouring Montenegro and onwards to Serbia.
