<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs facing test over salary link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS BY the government to curb a politically embarrassing rise in top
civil servants' salaries may provoke a row with MPs whose pay is linked to
the rates paid in Whitehall.
Ministers have belatedly discovered that plans to alter civil servants'
scales would trigger a debate followed by a Commons vote that they could not
guarantee to win.
The difficulty arises from the automatic linkage between an MP's salary  -
currently Pounds 30,854 - and a specified point on the salary scale for
senior civil servants. Under new pay arrangements, which the government is
still discussing with Whitehall unions, that scale disappears.
While a broadly equivalent linkage point could be found under the new
arrangements, the obstacle is that it would require a Commons vote. On
previous such occasions, MPs have refused to accept government advice about
the need for modest rises only.
Mr John Major has been kept informed of progress on the issue because of its
sensitivity at present.
The cabinet is today set to reject the independent recommendations of the
Top Salaries Review Body for pay rises of up to 30 per cent for senior
public servants, and for a substantial increase in an MP's office costs
allowance.
Rises for senior civil servants, judges and generals will be confined
instead to single figures.
The need for a review of MPs' pay will turn on whether the current Commons
motion is broad enough to apply when fixed salary scales are replaced by
ranges.
The Treasury admitted yesterday that 'there could be a need to change the
resolution'. In the event of a Commons debate, MPs and not the government
would decide the new salary arrangements. Party whips traditionally do not
apply on the issue.
The move to salary ranges for civil servants is intended to bring greater
flexibility, so that pay within each grade can be tailored to individual
performance.
</TEXT>
