FT  09 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Winterton anger at committee move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FIERCE row over government interference in MPs' rights to scrutinise its
activities exploded last night after the controversial Conservative chairman
of the health select committee claimed Tory whips had blocked his
re-appointment.
Mr Nicholas Winterton, the Macclesfield MP who has often criticised the
government, said the move was 'blatant interference' by business managers in
the supposedly neutral work of the selection committee which names each
body's members.
Despite Mr John Major's pledge to open government, he said, 'the politics of
dissent' were being crushed by the imposition of 'obedience, obedience,
obedience.'
Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP restored to the social services committee in
1987 after Mr Winterton interceded for him in similar circumstances, is now
to return the favour. He will table an amendment to the committee
selections, substituting Mr Winterton for another Tory MP.
However, neither man was confident last night that the amendment would be
carried after a clearly intentional demonstration by government business
managers of their muscle.
Labour is expected to take the chairmanship of six committees, including the
social security committee, which is poised to revive its investigation into
the Maxwell affair.
Mr John Watts, Conservative MP for Slough, was last night emerging as
favourite to become chairman of the Treasury select committee, replacing Mr
Terence Higgins.
However, Tory MPs on the trade and industry committee are threatening to
rebel against the Conservative whips' decision to give the chairmanship to
Labour - probably either Mr Doug Hoyle, MP for Warrington North, or Stan
Orme, MP for Salford East. A possible Tory candidate would be Sir Anthony
Grant, MP for Cambridgeshire South West.
The selection committee's decisions, based on the nominations of party
whips, will be announced today and debated on Monday.
