<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Sotheby's relieved at sale of Rembrandt: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WAVE of relief washed over the auction room at Sotheby's yesterday as
Rembrandt's impressive portrait of Johannes Uyttenbogaert was knocked down
at Pounds 3.8m (Pounds 4.18m with premium).
It was bought by Dr Otto Naumann, a dealer, on behalf of the man sitting
beside him, Dr Alfred Bader, a Milwaukee-based collector of Dutch
17th-century painting - predominantly of the Rembrandt school.
Dealers and collectors have been playing a waiting game to see what happens
in the market for Old Masters. Sotheby's showed signs of nervousness ahead
of yesterday's auction and can seldom have expended more energy on trying to
find buyers.
The picture - which had an impeccable country house provenance and the
blessing of the Rembrandt Research Project - was offered with an extremely
cautious estimate of Pounds 3m-plus. A small Rembrandt panel bought in at
Christie's in April had drawn bids up to Pounds 6m.
A Sotheby's saleroom notice announced that an overseas purchaser who applied
for an export licence immediately after the auction would not be obliged to
pay the purchase price until after the licence was granted - or in six
months if that were sooner.
Mr Julien Stock, head of Sotheby's Old Master department, said he had known
before the sale that he had a buyer but not an underbidder - a second
interested person to bid up the price.
Dr Naumann also secured a striking canvas by Giulio Cesare Procaccini of a
strangely smiling Judith clutching the head of Holofernes. It was offered
with a low estimate of Pounds 25,000-Pounds 35,000 and realised Pounds
209,000.
Guido Reni's David with the Head of Goliath, the second main lot of the
sale, fared less well. Mr Stock said there had been four serious contenders
for the picture but none materialised on the day. Bidding on the picture
stopped at Pounds 1.25m - one bid more would have secured it.
The vendor was one of many at Sotheby's - and tomorrow at Christie's -
prepared to sell at a considerable loss. The Reni canvas was bought for
Pounds 2m at Sotheby's in 1985 when the National Gallery in London had hoped
to acquire it.
Bidding on Lucas Cranach the Elder's sensual personification of Justice
crept up to Pounds 350,000, and a number of lots sold surprisingly well. An
extravagant architectural capriccio by Francisco Gutierrez made Pounds
181,500 (estimate Pounds 30,000 plus) and another 17th-century Spanish
picture, a still life by Juan de Espinosa, realised Pounds 143,000. The
morning session totalled Pounds 7,422,800 with a respectable 71.32 per cent
sold by value.
</TEXT>
