<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Industry praise for British Gas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE QUARTERS of industrial gas consumers are satisfied with the service
they receive from British Gas, according to a survey released today by Ernst
&amp; Young. Most welcome the introduction of competition into the gas market
but are concerned about possible supply difficulties.
The survey of more than 60 of the UK's biggest industrial consumers, as well
as independent marketers and Ofgas, the industry regulator, is the first
undertaken since the market was opened to competition in 1990. It was
carried out by the Industrial Research Bureau.
Its findings may surprise critics of British Gas as well as independent
suppliers who have pledged to outperform British Gas's standards of service.
The belief that prices would fall was the reason most consumers supported
increasing competition, although the survey found factors such as possible
shortfalls in production and supply might result in prices remaining stable.
Around 90 per cent of respondents believed competition would benefit
industrial customers. Some large users were concerned about the ability of
independent shippers to supply gas in sufficient quantities.
Two thirds of users said they would not risk changing suppliers simply for
the sake of lower prices, but many said they were likely to buy from more
than one source.
Consumers said British Gas should continue to provide storage facilities for
independents who were unable to make the necessary investment, but should be
allowed a fair rate of return. British Gas looks set to clash with Ofgas
after insisting that the rate of return on its pipeline and storage business
should be 6.7 per cent on existing assets and 10.8 per cent on new
investments.
Many felt competition could be achieved more quickly if there was more
discussion - and less confrontation - between Ofgas and British Gas.
Overall, 75 per cent of large industrial consumers said the service they
received from British Gas was either 'outstanding' or 'above average'.
British Gas and Rhone-Poulenc, the French chemicals and pharmaceuticals
group, have formed a jointly managed company to provide combined heat and
electricity to up to 10 of Rhone-Poulenc's 30 sites in the UK. British Gas
is investing up to Pounds 30m in the new company, Rhone-Poulenc Energy. It
will install and operate gas-fired plant, with the potential to sell surplus
power.
</TEXT>
