FT  09 JUL 92 / Court call for delay on payments to creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORMAL approval of the proposed once-and-for-all payments to creditors of
BCCI should be delayed until the creditors have been consulted, Luxembourg's
state prosecutor said yesterday.
The Luxembourg court must approve the provisional agreement - worked out by
the bank's liquidators and its majority shareholder, the Abu Dhabi
government - before it can be implemented.
If the formal decision is delayed, it could prolong the often acrimonious
dispute between disgruntled independent creditors and the Abu Dhabi
authorities over the terms of the deal. The judge, Mrs Maryse Welter, will
deliver her ruling on July 20.
The provisional settlement would involve a payment of between Dollars 1.2bn
(Pounds 620m) and Dollars 1.7bn to creditors and has been approved by courts
in Britain and the Cayman Islands. But Luxembourg, where BCCI had its
brass-plate headquarters, has the final word.
BCCI's liquidators disclosed during yesterday's hearing that Abu Dhabi was
limiting their access to more than 60,000 documents relating to the bank.
The emirate's lawyers argued the government had done its best to make all
the necessary documents available to the liquidators. But the judge
indicated they had not done enough. 'It sounds as though some of those
dossiers - on loans, for example - would be useful, perhaps indispensable
(to the liquidators' investigations),' she said.
Lawyers for independent BCCI creditors in the UK and Luxembourg have been
fighting to prevent implementation of the settlement, which they believe is
not generous enough.
Lawyers for the Abu Dhabi government again warned creditors of the 'serious
risks' involved in turning down the offer. 'Unless the majority shareholders
choose to make a voluntary payment the creditors may get nothing,' Mr Louis
Schiltz, counsel to the Abu Dhabi authorities, told the court yesterday.
</TEXT>
