<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Channel 5 details VCR retuning fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE army of video recorder retuners needed to make the Channel 5 commercial
television station possible are going to be paid by results - at a basic fee
of Pounds 1.50 a home.
The details of how Channel Five Holdings, the only bidder for the Channel 5
licence, plans to visit every home in London and then in other cities are
spelt out in the full application document, published yesterday.
It will be the biggest door-to-door operation since homes were converted to
natural gas in the 1960s. The retuning of VCRs and other electronic
equipment is necessary because the Channel 5 signal will cause interference.
The consortium, led by Thames Television, plans to put more than 2,000
retuners each in charge of 2,000 homes in their area.
After training, the contracted workforce will be responsible for retuning as
many as possible of their designated homes in a five-month period before
Channel 5 transmission begins.
In addition to the basic payment of Pounds 1.50 a home, there will be
bonuses of 40p if 90 per cent of the work is completed before transmissions
begin.
After broadcasts have started, bonuses can be earned by the speed of
response to complaints of interference.
In a field trial in the Harrow area of London, retuning took an average of
10 minutes from arriving on the doorstep. In 10 working days, 61 per cent of
the 725 households involved were successfully retuned without any publicity
or prearranged appointments.
Thorn UK Rentals will be responsible for recruiting and training the main
retuning workforce.
</TEXT>
