<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Competition policy 'lacks deterrent'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CURRENT competition policy fails to deter business from adopting or
considering anti-competitive behaviour, according to the former senior
economics adviser to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Writing in the Consumers' Association's Consumer Policy Review, Mr Robin
Aaronson says most UK companies look at competition policy in the wrong way
and do not plan rationally around the constraints it imposes.
As evidence, he quoted Tate &amp; Lyle, a company with nearly half the market
for a product, which bid twice for the company with the other half. Both
attempts were rejected after referral.
He says that all the evidence suggests a failure by the corporate sector to
balance regulatory risk against commercial advantage.
Competition policy in the UK is effective only when the authorities make a
direct intervention in a particular case. Its deterrent effect is much
weaker.
The costs of such lack of knowledge and understanding to the economy are
severe, he says. Large sums are spent on planning mergers and complying with
the Takeover Code and wasted when mergers are blocked.
Small businesses damaged by anti-competitive behaviour may go out of
business before the authorities have time to take action. Consumers suffer
directly by paying excessive prices for longer than they should.
Mr Aaronson suggests that policy changes could encourage business to take
more account of competition issues. In particular, the system of guidance to
companies offered by the Office of Fair Trading could be improved. The
authorities could also help if they gave clear explanations of their
decisions.
Mr Aaronson says the proliferation of competition authorities also causes
confusion, and combining the roles of the MMC and the OFT might provide a
solution.
Writing in the same issue of Consumer Policy Review, however, MMC chairman
Sir Sydney Lipworth says the OFT and MMC should not be merged.
</TEXT>
