<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / OFT probes music royalties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM LAWRENCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading has written to the Performing Right Society about
changes to the society's live-performance royalty system, which have angered
classical composers.
Before January, the society paid live royalties to composers using a formula
based on a full census of classical programmes. Now it makes its
calculations according to data from about 550 'significant' venues and 50
arts festivals, selected on the basis of capacity and the number of concerts
held each year.
The Composers' Guild of Great Britain claims that little-known composers
will lose when the first payments are made next July, because performances
at small concert venues will not be taken into account.
The society says the previous system was unfair, ineffective and
inefficient. Non-classical writers earned only from performances in large
venues and half of the classical performances went unreported in spite of
the huge administrative cost of chasing every programme - nearly a fifth of
the society's total revenue last year of Pounds 137m.
Ms Sarah Rogers, who chairs the composers' guild, said: 'The new live music
policy, far from creating a level playing field, has begun to reveal the
uneven workings of a monopoly.'
Ms Terri Anderson, the society's public-affairs controller, said composers
could not keep track on their own of where their music was performed and the
society could function only if its administrative costs were covered.
The dispute is likely to come to a head tonight at the society's annual
meeting.
The OFT confirmed that it had written to the society, asking to see the
directive on the collection of royalties and a copy of the society's
memorandum and articles of assistance.
</TEXT>
