FT  09 JUL 92 / Yorkshire TV faces fresh licence battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITE Rose Television, the defeated bidder for the Yorkshire television
franchise, has called formally on the Independent Television Commission to
revoke Yorkshire Television's licence.
White Rose claims that Yorkshire will be unable to fulfil its programme
promises because of its high bid and the fact that since the licence was
awarded competition has increased and the advertising recession has
continued.
White Rose, which bid Pounds 17.4m to Yorkshire's Pounds 37.7m, has made its
100-page submission to the ITC backed by counsel's opinion under section 18
of the 1990 Broadcasting Act. The section says a licence can be revoked
before it comes into effect if the ITC has reasonable grounds for believing
that the promised service will not be provided.
In a letter to Sir George Russell, ITC chairman, White Rose chairman Mr
Richard Hanwell says: 'We all recognise the quality of YTV's proposed
service - however, it is now certain that this service will never be
delivered because of that company's impossibly high bid.'
Yorkshire, in which Financial Times owner Pearson has a 20 per cent stake,
said: 'Yorkshire has been advised that there is no legal basis for White
Rose's submission and it is totally without merit.'
White Rose estimates that Yorkshire will have to pay 36.5 per cent of its
net advertising revenues to the government next year.
The Yorkshire case, based on cash rather than percentages, is that next year
the company is likely to have a gross cash margin of more than Pounds 90m
after payments to the government.
