<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Bank BCCI response attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, RALPH ATKINS and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FORMER chairman of the Commons Treasury committee yesterday attacked the
Bank of England for failing to respond properly to MPs' criticisms of the
Bank's supervision of Bank of Credit and Commerce International before its
closure.
The Bank yesterday conceded - in its formal response to the committee report
 -that some reform of the system of policing banks was needed in the wake of
the BCCI affair, although it defended the behaviour of its officials.
Mr Terence Higgins, Tory chairman of the committee in the last parliament,
complained that the Bank's response did not 'cover any of the criticisms
made of the Bank'. He added that the Bank was still not taking 'as tough a
line for the future as the committee proposed'.
Nonetheless, yesterday's response from the Bank shows a change of heart on
whether an auditor should have a 'right' or a 'duty' to inform the Bank of
England when it fears that there is malpractice at a bank or that
depositors' funds may be at risk.
Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the Bank governor, told the committee last year
that the present legal position, which gives auditors a right to report to
the Bank, was adequate. But the Bank now feels auditors should be obliged to
make such reports. The question is controversial because of the duty of
confidentiality owed by an auditor to its client.
The Bank said any amendment to the Banking Act would need to be carefully
drafted, to avoid it being swamped with auditors' reports.
Professional auditors responded positively to the Bank's suggestions
yesterday, while saying they would need extra protection if they were to
take on an enhanced whistleblowing role.
Mr Bill Morrison, chairman of the Auditing Practices Board, said: 'If it was
accompanied by a clarification of how auditors are protected by privilege
from breach of confidentiality, it is something people would be prepared to
consider.'
The Bank also said it wanted new powers to shut down a bank 'on the sole
ground that an applicant authorised bank cannot be effectively supervised'.
The Bank wants considerable latitude in the criteria for making such a
judgment.
It is asking for greater powers than those necessitated by its participation
earlier this week in an international agreement on co-operation between bank
regulators of the G10 leading industrial countries grouped in the Basle
Committee.
As implied by the Basle agreement, it wants to be able to close a bank if
that bank's domicile is in a country where the regulator lacks the expertise
or resources to take the lead role in supervising all the bank's operations.
The Bank also wants to be able to refuse authorisation to a bank if it sets
up branches in countries lacking an effective supervisor. That goes far
further than the Basle agreement.
The Bank also wants the right to withdraw authorisation if the nature of a
bank's business changes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
