FT  09 JUL 92 / Saudis may join EFA, claims US plane maker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US aircraft maker McDonnell Douglas yesterday intensified its efforts to
get US government support to sell 72 of its F-15 jet fighters to Saudi
Arabia, claiming that indecision in Washington could prompt the Saudis to
join the European Fighter Aircraft (EFA) programme as an equity partner.
McDonnell Douglas, which is financially stretched and faces a sharp decline
in US defence contract work, is anxious to keep its F-15 production line
open past 1994, when it will finish its last jet for the US Defence
Department. But the Bush administration has been putting off a decision on
the Saudi sale, which would raise controversy in Congress.
In a paper published yesterday, McDonnell Douglas said that the recent
German withdrawal from the EFA, along with US government indecision, 'sets
the stage for Saudi Arabia to join Britain, Italy and Spain as an equity
partner in a restructured European warplane project'.
The paper cited various newspaper articles to support this contention. Even
so, there seems to have been no official suggestion of Saudi equity
involvement, although British Aerospace has indicated that Saudi Arabia
might buy EFAs.
