<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / European Court backs away from Sunday trade row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE on the government to introduce urgent reform of Sunday trading laws
increased yesterday after the European Court of Justice suggested it was up
to English courts to sort out the confusion surrounding the present
legislation.
Mr Walter Van Gerven, the advocate-general, said it was justifiable under
Community law for countries to have national legislation which prohibited
shops opening on Sundays. He was giving a preliminary opinion in three cases
brought by local authorities in England and Wales against Payless DIY, B&amp;Q
and Anders - all DIY chains.
It was up to the English courts to decide whether the 1950 Shops Act was
incompatible with EC law and to judge whether the effect of general Sunday
closing on trade within the EC was disproportionate to the legitimate
objectives of the legislation.
The advocate-general's opinion is not binding on the full European Court,
which will deliver its judgment in the autumn. It will then be left to the
law lords, who referred the cases to Luxembourg, to decide the issue, taking
the court's views into account.
The government has been committed to reform of the Sunday trading laws since
1987 but has been reluctant to legislate after its last attempt was defeated
by a Conservative backbench rebellion in 1986.
Mr Stanley Kalms, chairman of Dixons, the electrical retailer, said
yesterday he had received a personal promise 'from a politician higher than
Kenneth Clarke', the home secretary, that the government would introduce
legislation immediately after the European Court ruling was published this
autumn.
Retailers who have been close to discussions with the government suggest any
legislation is likely to enshrine three main principles: a commitment to
keep Sunday trading different from Saturday, perhaps by specifying a maximum
number of trading hours; a commitment to help protect small shops; and a
provision to protect employee rights.
The government is believed to be keen to prevent the passage of Labour MP Mr
Ray Powell's private member's bill, which suggests reforms along the lines
of proposals drawn up by the Keep Sunday Special Campaign. These seek an
updating of the Sunday trading laws, with heavy regulation and greater
clarification.
The share prices of many of the leading retail companies involved in Sunday
trading were hit yesterday but most recovered as the day progressed.
Kingfisher, which owns the B&amp;Q chain, ended the day down 4p at 466p; J
Sainsbury closed down 3p at 449p; Argyll Group, owner of Safeway, was down
5p at 343p; and Tesco was down 4p at 254p.
Lex, Page 22
London stocks, Page 42
</TEXT>
