FT  09 JUL 92 / Dixons falls 14% and sees no upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIXONS, the UK's biggest electrical retailing chain which is widely viewed
in the City as being one of the first beneficiaries of any economic
recovery, said yesterday sales had slipped back in recent weeks as it
reported a 14 per cent fall in annual profits to Pounds 70.3m.
The company's shares shed 9p to 214p on the news that there were 'no real
signs in the UK and US of any sustained economic upturn' and helped
precipitate a weakening of many other stocks in the stores sector.
In January, Mr Stanley Kalms, Dixons' chairman, described how consumers in
some parts of the country 'were bouncing with enthusiasm' with sales
increases running in the 'mid-teens'.
Yesterday he said sales had weakened over the past nine weeks but were still
running 'slightly ahead' of last year. 'We are quite shattered that the
trend has turned off its line,' he said.
In the year to May 2, however, Dixons recorded a continued resurgence of
profitability in the UK, where it runs the Dixons, Currys and Supasnaps
chains. UK operating profits rose one third to Pounds 71.9m on sales 11 per
cent higher at Pounds 1.2bn.
Dixons said the improvement largely stemmed from the greater operating
efficiencies from its growing portfolio of edge-of-town Currys superstores.
Fourteen more were opened during the year bringing the total to 115, while
43 Currys high street stores were shut.
Sales of consumer electronics, household appliances and photographic
equipment remained weak but computer games, business computers and
camcorders showed good gains.
The UK profits were inflated by the inclusion of Pounds 10m from the release
of excess provisions from its product warranties.
Dixons' Silo chain in the US fell into a Pounds 16.9m loss (from Pounds 3.5m
profit) on sales of Pounds 580.9m.
The company's UK and European property interests contributed profits of
Pounds 4.1m (down from Pounds 11m). Total group turnover rose 10 per cent to
Pounds 1.86bn. Dixons swallowed an Pounds 11.2m extraordinary charge
relating mainly to provisions for discontinuing UK property development.
Earnings per share fell from 12.6p to 9.5p. A final dividend of 4.4p lifted
the total 3 per cent to 6p.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
