<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Olympia and York is not only one in trouble because of building schemes in
docklands. Business Matters reckons that 100 smaller construction companies
went into receivership during the building of Canary Wharf, most because
they could not get their money from the big boys for work they had
completed. The programme investigates the growing problem of late payment to
sub-contractors (7.30 BBC2).
If there have already been full-length profiles of Ross Perot on British
television I have missed them. This Week fills the gap with a portrait of
the Dallas businessman who is running neck and neck with George Bush and
Bill Clinton in the race for the US presidency, though he has not even
declared his candidacy (8.30 ITV). Wildlife Showcase documents the return of
three dolphins, previously held in dolphinariums, to the sea off the West
Indies (8.30 BBC2).
In True Stories a collection of remarkable short films about life in
post-communist St Petersburg, shown earlier this year on C4, is edited into
a single 90-minute programme. Much of the time it seems as though a war is
going on, without anybody knowing who the enemy is (9.30).
