<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour to address backbench concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR backbenchers are taking steps to counteract the possibility that Mr
John Smith might develop a 'bunker mentality' after he is elected leader of
the opposition at the end of next week.
After years of behind-the-scenes griping that Mr Neil Kinnock's staff
overprotected the leader from his troops, several MPs are taking precipitate
action to ensure clearer lines of communication are kept open to the new
leadership.
Yesterday, Mr Graham Allen, the Nottingham North MP, won unopposed support
at the parliamentary Labour party weekly meeting for a general review of the
organisation and workings of the PLP, aimed at involving backbench MPs more
closely in decision-making.
Aware of the mood within the party, Mr Smith had already promised such a
review when he made his leadership campaign presentation to the party last
month.
Mr Derek Foster, the chief whip re-elected last week, also made representing
backbench interests an important element in his campaign.
In a letter to MPs, Mr Allen emphasised his motion for a review committee
was 'entirely constructive'. He added yesterday: 'In the past, in order to
get a helpful suggestion considered you had to create a campaign or a row.
There should be a mechanism whereby good ideas as well as discontent can be
expressed.'
Under his proposed review committee, the PLP chairman, three nominated
shadow cabinet members and three elected MPs would meet regularly to discuss
issues and report back to the PLP.
Supporters of Mr Smith say he will conduct his leadership in a more
collegiate style than Mr Kinnock, thereby provoking less of the 'insiders
and outsiders' divisions complained of by the left.
However, some more cynical MPs say that whatever the well-meaning intentions
of the party's leader-to-be, the fierce rivalries within the PLP inevitably
lead to a bunker mentality emerging.
</TEXT>
