FT  09 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Plans for committees spark row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT business managers yesterday precipitated a Commons row over the
departmental select committee system by trying to remove the Tory chairman
of the health committee and giving Labour the chairmanship of the trade and
industry committee.
Labour is expected to take the chairmanship of six committees, including the
social security committee, which is poised to revive its investigation into
the Maxwell affair.
Mr John Watts, Conservative MP for Slough, was last night emerging as
favourite to become chairman of the Treasury select committee. He will
replace Mr Terence Higgins, who is leaving the committee.
However, Tory MPs on the trade and industry committee are threatening to
rebel against the Conservative whips' decision to give the chairmanship to
Labour - probably either Mr Doug Hoyle, MP for Warrington North, or Stan
Orme, MP for Salford East. A possible Tory candidate would be Sir Anthony
Grant, MP for Cambridgeshire South West.
The departmental select committees have grown considerably in importance
since being set up first in 1979. The televising of their proceedings has
increased their powers to intimidate the executive by calling ministers and
officials to give evidence.
The selection committee's decisions, based on the nominations of party
Whips, will be announced today and be debated on Monday. Each committee will
then meet before the summer recess to chose a chairman - possibly
overturning the whips' intentions - and discuss a possible inquiry
programme.
Certain to protest is Mr Nicholas Winterton, the Conservative chairman of
the health committee of the last parliament, who frequently criticised
government policy. The selection committee agreed last night to remove him
from the list of MPs proposed for the health brief.
Mr Winterton yesterday complained that the Tory whips were 'bully boys'
acting 'on behalf of the establishment'.
Among other committees, Mr Frank Field, Labour MP for Birkenhead, is set to
retain the chairmanship of social security; Mr David Howell, Tory MP for
Guildford, should win foreign affairs; and Sir John Wheeler, MP for
Westminster North, should keep home affairs.
Besides trade and industry and social security, Labour is also expected to
take the chairmanships of the Welsh and Scottish committees, employment and
the newly created national heritage committee.
</TEXT>
