FT  09 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: BR sale to stress quality of
service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT ministers will next week try to present the privatisation of
British Rail as an opportunity to improve service quality before the next
general election, Ralph Atkins writes.
The long-awaited white paper on BR's privatisation will stress the possible
benefits in terms of increased flexibility in rail services, improved
customer service and lower fares. The department regards the sell-off as
unique in that there will be less emphasis on the amount it will raise for
the Treasury.
Legislation for the sale allowing private-sector companies to bid to run
services is expected to be brought before parliament after the summer
recess, with the first franchises in 1994.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, is expected to argue that the
continuing high level of public subsidy for the railways continuing means
the government will continue to have a say over the level of services. No
rush for franchises is expected.
His department has been talking with private-sector companies, particularly
those already involved in transport, about possible deals and about the
transfer of more freight on to rail. BR's freight division will be sold
outright.
