FT  09 JUL 92 / Engineering workers reject 5% pay offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than 1,300 engineering workers yesterday rejected a 5 per cent pay
offer that involved the introduction of performance pay and the end of
collective bargaining.
Pay has been frozen for 18 months at the two British Timken engineering
parts factories near Northampton, according to the AEEU engineering and
electrical union, which represents the manual workforce.
Performance pay has grown rapidly in the private sector for white-collar and
professional workers, particularly in financial services, but is uncommon
among manual workers.
Members of the union voted to reject the proposed package by a majority of
70 per cent at British Timken's factory at Daventry and by a majority of 85
per cent at its Duston site. The union had not directed the workforce to
reject the offer.
Mr Duncan Simpson, AEEU divisional organiser, said the union would 'consider
its position' should the company decide to impose the package.
