<DATE>920709
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / DTI to ease disclosure rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUND managers would not be required to disclose stakes below 10 per cent in
companies held by clients, under rules proposed by the Department of Trade
and Industry. The present ceiling is 3 per cent.
The DTI has been under pressure from the Institutional Fund Managers
Association, the industry trade association, to ease disclosure requirements
that fund managers say are expensive and unnecessary.
'In no way would you say that these stakes are predatory,' said Mr Richard
Weir, director general of the IFMA.
The DTI first consulted on its draft directive in February 1991 and its
proposed rules have been prepared in the light of its consultation and other
developments since then.
The proposed rules are set out in a paper being circulated within the
industry. They will apply to fund managers charged with buying, selling and
voting shares held in segregated accounts in the names of individual
clients.
At present, fund managers whose sole job it is to sell shares on behalf of
clients need give notification only of stakes of 15 per cent or more. That
ceiling will be lowered to 10 per cent under the proposals.
The rules say stakes in companies in pooled funds managed by fund managers
need be disclosed only when they reach 10 per cent.
While the directive is generally a relaxation of notification rules, they
will be tightened in respect of unlisted companies. For the first time,
stakes in unlisted companies of 10 per cent or more will have to be
disclosed as well.
The fund management industry has argued for a relaxation of notification
requirements, saying the present rules are cumbersome and expensive to
administer. Large fund managers typically need a half-time to a full-time
staff person simply to administer notifications at a cost of Pounds 15,000
to Pounds 20,000 a year.
IFMA also argues that no European country has a requirement to disclose
stakes below 10 per cent and a 1988 directive set 10 per cent as the minimum
size of a notifiable position.
Nevertheless, in what is likely to be a disappointment to the pension funds
industry, the DTI declined to lift the ceiling on notifiable stakes held by
pension fund trustees. In its original proposal, the DTI suggested that
trustees should be subject to the 10 per cent rule, rather than the current
3 per cent ceiling.
In its paper, circulated to the industry, the DTI said it had decided to
take no action on trustees' holdings. It cited a wide-ranging go-vernment
review of pension law.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14223</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGIA7AA1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920709
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / Kevin Maxwell wins order on debts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kevin Maxwell, faced with an income-tax demand which he says he is unable
to meet, was yesterday granted an interim High Court order that temporarily
stops creditors bringing civil proceedings against him.
At a private hearing before a Chancery Court registrar, Mr Maxwell, son of
the late Robert Maxwell, won an order under Section 252 of the 1986
Insolvency Act allowing him time to seek an 'individual voluntary
arrangement' with his creditors.
Mr George Auger, of accountants Stoy Hayward, was appointed to act as his
nominee in seeking the arrangement.
Mr Maxwell said through his solicitors, Peters &amp; Peters: 'A demand for the
payment of income tax by the Inland Revenue, which I was advised is due and
owing and which I am unable to meet, has precipitated my application today
for the interim order.
'I have taken this course solely to assist the realisation of my assets for
the benefit of all my creditors. I shall do all I can to that end.'
The order granted to Mr Maxwell today 'stays' all existing or pending civil
proceedings against him, including those brought by creditors, for 14 days
to give him time to prepare voluntary settlement proposals for consideration
by his nominee.
