FT  09 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Rushdie shadow over UK-Iran trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, Middle East Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Salman Rushdie affair is harming British companies' chances of winning
contracts in Iran, according to the British Consultants Bureau (BCB), a
non-profit group which promotes UK consultants overseas, and recently sent a
mission to Iran.
The eight-member mission said yesterday, after a 10-day trip to Tehran and
Isfahan, that British groups were falling behind US, Japanese and European
competitors in gaining contracts from Iran's ambitious plans for developing
its infrastructure. This follows the souring of relations because of the
late Ayatollah Khomeini's fatwa against Mr Salman Rushdie, whose book, the
Satanic Verses, Moslems regard as blasphemous.
Mr Nigel Thompson, a director of Ove Arup who led the mission, said Iran
offered a 'huge potential market' for UK groups, notably in petro-chemicals,
power, water and sewage schemes, but that Iranian officials wanted to see
the British government distance itself from Mr Rushdie.
The mission was critical of the level of official British commercial
representation in Iran, saying the embassy in Tehran was understaffed,
underinformed and should raise the status of its chief representative from
charge d'affaires, to full ambassador.
The mission, three of whom remained in Iran to pursue possible contracts in
transport, construction and water, also said they believed Britain should
extend the level of export credit financing available to Iran through the
Export Credits Guarantees Department (ECGD).
Iran is on medium to long-term cover from the ECGD, and the agency said
yesterday that cover for actual and potential contracts already exceeded the
country limit - a total demand estimated to be around Pounds 1bn.
</TEXT>
