<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Typewriter rivals in phantom factory feud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE trade bill debated by the House of Representatives yesterday includes a
controversial clause which would make it more difficult for foreign
companies to circumvent anti-dumping duties.
The bill's supporters, mostly Democrats, want to close a loophole in the
1988 trade law allowing foreign companies to avoid anti-dumping duties by
setting up 'phantom' factories in the US. These assembly operations import
all their parts from third countries which are not covered by the
anti-dumping order.
The bill would give the US Commerce Department added authority to judge
whether a company is evading anti-dumping duties by considering 'actual and
potential' threats to US industries. This change in the law primarily stems
from a trade feud between Smith Corona and Brother Industries of Japan.
Smith Corona accuses Brother of evading a dumping duty by assembling
typewriters at its Tennessee plant with parts imported from Singapore and
Malaysia.
Mr Lee Thompson, Smith Corona's chairman, says Brother set up the low-wage,
low-skill assembly plant expressly to circumvent the 60 per cent duty.
Brother admits it swallows losses to keep market share (a tacit admission of
dumping, argues Smith Corona). Mr Patrick O'Leary, the company's lawyer,
counter-attacks with the charge that Brother loses money because Smith
Corona dumped the US market with personal electric typewriters made in
Singapore.
The Japanese company filed its own anti-dumping case against Smith Corona.
However, the Commerce Department last year ruled Brother had no standing
because it did not qualify as as American manufacturer protected by the law;
the case is now in court.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
