<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Pentland to buy Adidas from BTF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PENTLAND Holdings, the UK consumer products company, yesterday ended weeks
of negotiations by agreeing to buy Adidas, the German sporting goods group,
from Bernard Tapie Finance (BTF), in a deal worth worth DM621m (Pounds
215m).
The transaction, which values Adidas at FFr3.1bn (Pounds 300m), ends
speculation about the future direction of cash-rich Pentland. The UK company
first set its sights on Adidas last summer, when it negotiated the purchase
of 20 per cent stake and an option on a further 5 per cent in BTF for Pounds
46m.
Pentland became a stock market favourite in the 1980s on the windfall
Dollars 777m profit from its investment in Reebok, the US sports shoe
company. Mr Frank Farrant, Pentland finance director, insisted the company
had not been 'bounced into a deal' by press speculation about management
bids.
'Pentland had always made it clear we would be very interested in taking
control of this company at the right price,' Mr Farrant said. 'If you look
at the price we paid relative to the DM1bn that was mooted last week, it is
a very good price.'
The deal is a watershed for Mr Tapie, who has been struggling to repay debts
he took on to buy Adidas two years ago.
Pentland has agreed to pay DM621m in cash for BTF's 58 per cent stake in BTF
GmbH and also to buy out the other minority investors. Pentland's shares
rose 14p to 144p in London. BTF's shares remained suspended in Paris at
FFr130.
