   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAKS Fifth Avenue, the upmarket US retailer, incurred after-tax losses of
Dollars 398m in the 19 months to January 31 1992, AP-DJ reported yesterday.
It said the figure was disclosed in 'a confidential Saks document' obtained
by Dow Jones.
Yesterday, Mr Arthur Martinez, Saks' vice-chairman, declined to comment on
any specific figures. However, he stressed that the retailer faced no
liquidity problems and had breached no banking covenants. Saks was acquired
from Britain's BAT Industries in 1990 by Investcorp, an investment company
backed by Middle Eastern funds.
Earlier this year, Saks announced that Investcorp was injecting another
Dollars 300m of equity into the retailer - a move which came amid rumours of
poor operating performance and late payments to suppliers. The latter was
emphatically denied, although Saks said trading was 'clearly very
difficult'. Yesterday, Mr Martinez said again that this move was unconnected
to trading results, and designed to continue the 'deleveraging' of the
company.
