<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Lamont warned of flawed forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY has been told to take all forecasts about the UK economy in the
next few years - including its own - with several bucketloads of salt.
These projections are likely to be deeply flawed because of a lack of
knowledge about how the economy works, and in particular those aspects
linked to financial deregulation, according to preliminary results from a
study financed by the Treasury.
The analysis by the independent National Institute for Economic and Social
Research is a painful rebuke for most economic forecasters and raises
awkward questions for Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, as he struggles to
end the recession.
The analysis was sponsored by the Treasury to gain better insights into
inadequacies in its own forecasting methods. Government economists - as well
as those in the City and in academic institutes - failed to foresee the
extent both of the 1986-88 boom and of the current recession.
In the most authoritative study yet into these failings, Mr Andrew Britton
and Mr Nigel Pain of the institute say the Treasury and most outside
forecasters were equally inaccurate, probably because the standard computer
models of how the economy works are faulty.
It suggests the Treasury's techniques to calculate the effects of policy
switches such as interest rate shifts may not have caught up with the
financial reforms of the 1980s.
The study - results from which were released yesterday at a conference at
Warwick University on forecasting - says economists should take more notice
of advance indicators of activity such as housing starts, business
confidence and equity prices. It adds that most private sector economists
tend to take a consensus view to avoid extremes.
The report clears government statisticians - who have been blamed for some
of the Treasury's recent forecasting errors on the grounds that they failed
to measure the economy properly - of any substantial blame for the
inaccurate projections.
Looking at specific forecasters, the institute says economists at Shearson
Lehman Brothers, the US investment group, were 'perhaps the quickest to pick
up the trends within the economy'. The Confederation of British Industry,
the City University Business School and Liverpool University gain honourable
mentions and Professor Wynne Godley of Cambridge University is singled out
for giving an early warning of the recession. The Treasury said it was
looking at the results of the study to 'review directions for new research'.
According to Mr Britton and Mr Pain, a strong possibility is that
'structural change, due for example to financial deregulation, has changed
the parameters of a number of relationships (in economic models) . . . If
this is true, then it may be some years before sufficient data are available
to estimate those new parameter values correctly'.
The change triggered by financial liberalisation is 'particularly worrying
because it could mean that we do not know how the economy responds to
instruments of monetary policy'.
Editorial Comment, Page 20
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
