<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Cabinet set to reject top pay rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government appears set to reject the recommendations of an independent
review body that more than 2,000 top public servants should receive a large
one-off pay rise to bring their salaries level with those in the private
sector, Philip Stephens writes.
Senior ministers expect tomorrow's meeting of the cabinet to scale back
significantly the increases for senior civil servants, armed forces officers
and judges suggested by the Top People's Pay Review Body. Mr John Major is
also likely to insist that those pay awards of over 10 per cent which are
accepted by the government should be phased in.
The board is thought to have recommended increases of more than 25 per cent
for some groups of workers to close the gap which has opened up between
comparable positions in the private and public sectors since 1986. One
cabinet minister this week described increases on that scale as 'totally
unacceptable'.
The prime minister, who has consistently criticised large pay awards for
executives in the private sector, will be told by colleagues that there is
no likelihood of an 'exodus' of senior public servants if he rejects large
pay awards.
Mr Major's colleagues, facing one of the toughest public spending rounds in
recent years, will argue that large increases for high-paid public sector
workers would send the wrong signal to other groups of employees. They
expect the prime minister to agree that any increase this year should be
held to 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
