<DATE>920708
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Portillo tries to tug at the reins
of a few favourites - Philip Stephens looks at the gloomy prospects that
will surround the coming season of public-spending negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Michael Portillo explains to cabinet colleagues how serious he is
about restraining public spending, he begins with a disarming reflection on
his own recent career.
He begins by conceding that for each of them, the loss of a cherished
project or cuts in a priority programme in this year's negotiations will
cause painful political embarrassment.
Then the chief secretary to the Treasury reminds his colleagues that he
knows more than most about such embarrassment. As local-government minister
under Mrs Margaret Thatcher he had been a public and committed champion of
the poll tax, he recalls. Re-appointed by Mr John Major, he was charged -
against his better judgment and at considerable personal cost - with its
abolition.
The message is clear. Mr Portillo will not be impressed by pleading that the
scrapping of a planned roads scheme or the shelving of a new training
programme would cause his colleagues undue discomfort in the House of
Commons.
So far, no blood has actually been spilt in the negotiating skirmishes,
although there has been the usual trickle of leaks about the Treasury's
prime targets - the defence, unemployment benefit, housing, roads and Home
Office budgets among them.
Looking over his shoulder at an economy still mired in recession and a
borrowing requirement heading for Pounds 35bn, Mr Major will deliver a stern
lecture on the need for prudence when he chairs a decidedly downbeat cabinet
discussion on the economic outlook later this month. The real battles will
then be fought in September and October.
No one is in any doubt that they will be tough. In spite of a pre-election
spree, Whitehall officials acknowledge that on present trends the Treasury
will miss its Pounds 226.6bn spending target for the current 1992-93
financial year.
Some Pounds 450m has already been taken from the Pounds 4bn contingency
reserve to pay for the teachers' pay award, for increased income support for
pensioners and for health-service wage settlements.
That figure does not include the huge cost of higher unemployment. The
number out of work is already more than 300,000 above the 2.4m allowed for
in the present spending plans. It is still rising and, on a conservative
estimate, the higher jobless total will cost an extra Pounds 2bn this year
and Pounds 3bn next.
It will further cloud a bleak medium-term outlook.
In the five years from 1985-86 to 1989-90 the Treasury's planning total  -
the departmental allocations that provide the main instrument of expenditure
control - remained flat in real terms.
For the subsequent five years - from 1990-91 to 1994-95 - the Treasury's
plans already assume an increase after inflation of 20 per cent.
That figure assumes heroically that Mr Portillo will not add a penny to the
targets, but if the Treasury cannot win in the first spending round after a
general election, it never will.
A large part of the prospective increase - perhaps half - can be attributed
to the recession. The rest reflects a conscious loosening of the reins in
the approach to the general election. It will not be easy to re-tighten
them.
Mr Portillo's starting point is a planning total for 1993-94 of Pounds
244.5bn and for 1994-95 of Pounds 258bn. He must also pencil in a figure for
1995-96.
In theory the totals, which include sizeable reserves, allow for ample
growth in Whitehall spending - an average in real terms of 3.5 per cent in
each of the next two years. That follows a planned increase of 5.75 per cent
in the current year.
In practice, most of the additional money will be absorbed by the higher
benefit payments to the unemployed and by the additions to local-authority
budgets needed to smooth the introduction next April of the council tax.
Transitional relief schemes to ease the impact of the council tax in the
recession-hit south-east might well cost Pounds 1.25bn next year. Local
authorities will need another Pounds 1bn to allow even a small real increase
in spending.
So Mr Portillo cannot afford to allow other Whitehall departments any
increase in the 'baseline' figures agreed last year. Some of those budgets -
including for employment, housing, defence, transport, agriculture, and
trade and industry - already point to real cuts in spending. But to meet the
overall target, further reductions will be needed to pay for unavoidable
increases elsewhere.
The Treasury has already earmarked a number of 'soft' targets. It wants
drastic cuts in the Department of Transport's roads programme to pay for
increased financial support for British Rail and London Regional Transport.
It is casting a close eye over the Department of Education's capital
spending and at the Home Office's ambitious prison-building programme.
The Department of the Environment's housing budget - a beneficiary in recent
years of Mr Major's caring Conservatism - is another prime candidate.
Smaller reductions are expected from the DoE's green budget and that for
employment training.
Defence remains a cherished target because it has successfully resisted the
large savings that might have flowed from the collapse of communism. But
even if - as the Treasury expects - the European Fighter Aircraft is never
built, the peace dividend will take some years to materialise.
The Department of Social Security is under pressure to deliver reductions in
other benefits - including unemployment benefit - to help finance income
support and housing benefit payments for the jobless.
The health budget already includes a 2.75 per cent real increase in
spending. The Treasury would like some back to finance the care in the
community programme.
Senior ministers believe substantial cuts across Whitehall are possible. But
the chief secretary is as strong or weak as his prime minister; and to the
chagrin of his predecessor, the author of the Citizen's Charter has so far
proved himself more willing to spend than save.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
