<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory stamp duty rebellion subdued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROSPECTIVE rebellion over the re-introduction of stamp duty on house
purchases fizzled out in the Commons last night as Tory backbenchers stopped
short of supporting a Labour amendment to extend the current moratorium
until March 1993.
Not a single Conservative MP voted for the amendment which was defeated by
30 votes (281-311), although one - Mr John Wilkinson (C Ruislip-Northwood) -
indicated he would abstain.
This was in spite of considerable Conservative support for a parliamentary
early day motion tabled last month calling for 'a further extension' of the
relief - which applies to the purchase of houses costing up to Pounds
250,000 - after it runs out in six weeks' time.
For the government, Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury,
said the Opposition amendment would more than double the Pounds 400m cost of
the moratorium to date.
It was more important to pursue policies designed to reduce interest rates
and 'get a real grip on public expenditure.' The government should not try
to 'rekindle' confidence by 'fiscal and other measures that have the effect
of inflating house prices further.'
Sir Malcolm Thornton, the Tory MP for Crosby who tabled last month's early
day motion, said that while keeping the moratorium would help the building
and construction sector, he recognised the Treasury had 'enormous
difficulty' in balancing competing claims.
Signing an early day motion was a means of expressing an opinion and not 'a
gesture of rebellion,' he added.
Mr Wilkinson applauded Labour for introducing the amendment and argued that
stamp duty was 'a direct tax on flexibility and mobility in the employment
market.' The real need was for immediate measures to bring interest rates
down by some 2 1/2 per-centage points, he said.
For Labour, Mr John Marek, a front bench Treasury spokesman, called on the
government to support the amendment to show the original moratorium was not
just 'a gimmick for the election.'
</TEXT>
