FT  08 JUL 92 / Merit pay may hit women
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GROWTH of per-formance-related pay may widen the gap between male and
female earnings, the Equal Opportunities Commission said yesterday.
The EOC says merit pay tends to reward men more than women because employers
use it to adjust earnings to the market rate. Women's earnings are less
likely to contain a merit element, and the subjective and general nature of
many appraisal processes allows managers to make sexist judgments.
However its investigation into why women's earnings have stayed at about two
thirds of men's found evidence of a gradual move of women into higher-paid
posts previously filled by men.
Pay and Gender in Britain: 2. IRS 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
Pounds 25.
