FT  08 JUL 92 / BCCI report by Bank set to back tighter regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England is expected to respond today to the criticisms of a
Commons select committee and back stronger banking supervision laws after
the collapse of Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
Extra powers to act against banks whose opaque or internationally spread
structure makes regulation difficult are expected to be proposed by the Bank
in its formal response to the cross-party Treasury select committee
investigation into the affair.
However, the Bank is expected to wait until the publication of Lord Justice
Bingham's official inquiry into BCCI before it gives its detailed response
to specific criticisms of the closure of the bank more than a year ago.
The Bank has already rebuffed the MPs' general assertion that action could
have been taken against BCCI earlier than last summer's closure.
To the anger of Labour MPs, the Treasury is expected today to say it will
not publish its response to the Treasury select committee until after the
Bingham report - probably not until after MPs rise for the summer recess
next week.
Mr Giles Radice, Labour member of the treasury committee in the last
parliament, said: 'If a select committee acts quickly, like we did, and
tries to come up with something sensible about regulation of a dodgy bank
you would have thought that the government would at least have the courtesy
of responding quickly. The delay is becoming a major scandal.'
The Bank is understood to have compiled a 30-page response to the Treasury
committee's investigation into international and national banking
supervision laws and to have accepted a number of the MPs' recommendations.
Bank officials came in for most criticism in the report, with ministers
escaping blame.
The committee said troubles in BCCI's structure were recognised but its
'complicated international network' was tolerated.
An attempt by BCCI creditors to postpone a planned challenge to the High
Court's approval of a Dollars 1.7bn (Pounds 883m) compensation package
failed in the Court of Appeal yesterday, Raymond Hughes writes.
After the decision of the BCCI UK creditors' committee not to appeal against
last month's High Court ruling sanctioning the deal negotiated between
liquidators Touche Ross and the bank's Abu Dhabi majority shareholders, a
number of individuals want to take over the appeal.
Their application to be substituted as appellants is due to be heard next
Monday but yesterday their counsel, Mr David Hunt QC, asked for an
adjournment until July 20.
