<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Fears raised on reliability of equipment: Defence white
paper analyses lessons from Gulf war Women may move closer to front line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RELIABILITY of army land vehicles during the Gulf war was criticised
yesterday in the annual defence white paper.
It says unreliability had considerable implications for operations and was
overcome only by a disproportionate application of maintenance and spares.
Equipment and spares had to be borrowed or purchased from allied and
friendly countries.
In spite of such handicaps, preliminary lessons from the conflict suggested
that no big changes in British military doctrine and organisation were
required. The white paper says the Gulf campaign exposed a number of
shortcomings, although those should not detract from an outstandingly
successful operation.
It highlights difficulties during the campaign, providing the services with
opportunities to lobby for particular projects such as the the European
Fighter Aircraft and the army's new anti-tank helicopter.
The performance of Challenger 1, the British army's battle tank manufactured
by Vickers, is described merely as 'effective'. The tank's reliability and
fire-control system were limiting factors, the white paper says. Since the
conflict, the Ministry of Defence has put in an order for about 130
new-generation Challenger 2 tanks.
The white paper says older support and engineering vehicles were unable to
keep up with more modern equipment and had been left behind.
The report also lobbies for a replacement for the Lynx anti-tank helicopter.
It says the aircraft lacked the ability to withstand ground fire which is
required in a dedicated attack helicopter. The army has indicated a strong
preference for the American AH64 Apache. Westland of the UK has reached an
agreement with McDonnell Douglas of the US for a British-assembled version.
The Midge drone, used to provide airborne surveillance, proved unreliable
and unable to provide real-time information. A new remotely piloted vehicle,
called Phoenix, is due to replace the Midge in 1993.
The white paper attempts to explain why the Royal Air Force lost six Tornado
GR1 jets, but says it was not because they were flying low to use the
airfield-denying weapon, JP233. Only one jet was lost on a JP233 mission.
However, four of the aircraft were lost at low level, the only height where
the jet's sensors and weapon systems could be effectively employed. The
report concludes that the conflict demonstrated a need for a more flexible
approach to future RAF training requirements. It also argues that the
campaign showed the importance of achieving air superiority and the value of
an agile
British intelligence organisations are cleared by the white paper of
misreading Saddam Hussein's intentions. Intelligence resources at the time
were focused on the changes in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
The whole campaign cost the UK about Pounds 2.5bn, according to the paper.
The Ministry of Defence said yesterday that about Pounds 1.5bn had already
been supplied through burden-sharing and it expected approximately Pounds
500m to be provided before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
