<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / DPP backs calls on plea bargaining
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Barbara Mills, the director of public prosecutions, yesterday added her
voice to calls for a formal system of plea bargaining in English and Welsh
courts.
She said plea agreements worked out in open court where all parties knew
what was on offer were 'very sensible' and it was time to consider them.
Mrs Mills also said that formalising the system of sentence discounts for
defendants who plead guilty should be studied.
Presenting the Crown Prosecution Service's annual report, Mrs Mills said she
did not see an enhanced role for the CPS in the investigation of crimes as
the answer to miscarriages of justice, but thought there was a case for the
CPS giving more advice to the police before they charged suspects.
Last year 10 per cent of 1.5m cases handled by the CPS were discontinued
because the prosecution service disagreed with the police charges.
In response to the Competing for Quality white paper, published last
November, the CPS is also looking at functions that can be contracted out.
The National Audit Office yesterday called for urgent measures to control
the sharp rise in legal aid expenditure.
Sir John Bourn, head of the NAO, says in a report to parliament on legal aid
in England and Wales that expenditure rose 85 per cent - from Pounds 387m to
Pounds 717m - between 1986-87 and 1990-91. In 1991-92 the Lord Chancellor's
Department and the Legal Aid Board expect a 30 per cent overspend - Pounds
210m more than the approved estimate of Pounds 698m.
A review by Touche Ross, chartered accountants, suggested that legal aid
frauds by lawyers could total Pounds 6.4m a year through claims for work not
done.
