<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Era of efficiency and cost-cutting outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN may train to become commandos, the Citizen's Charter is to be enacted
at the Meteorological Office and a 'green minister', Lord Cranborne, has
been appointed at the Ministry of Defence. Those are just three of the ideas
in this year's defence white paper. But the underlying message is little
changed from last year: the 1990s will be a period of efficiency drives and
cost-cutting.
The commitment to developing 'smaller but better forces' following the
two-year-old Options for Change programme of cuts is restated. The
procurement side has been pruned in an effort to keep within the Treasury's
Pounds 24bn-Pounds 25bn target for annual spending until 1995.
One casualty is the Trigat medium-range anti-tank missile programme.
Spending plans now only take it through its development phase and not to
production. That cuts the cost of the project from Pounds 920m to Pounds
125m and follows a similar decision last year on the long-range version of
Trigat.
However, many spending plans do survive. They include the re-equipping of
the First Armoured Division with new tanks, armoured vehicles, artillery and
other systems that will increase its combat capabilities by 25 per cent by
1995, and by more than a third by 2000.
The white paper confirms that more plastic-hulled Sandown-class minehunters
will be ordered. That will provide some reassurance to Vosper Thornycroft,
the smallest of the UK's four warship yards, which last January announced
about 350 job losses, partly as the result of a postponement of the Royal
Navy order.
More than 75 per cent of defence contracts in the past year were placed by
competition or priced by reference to to market forces, the white paper
says. The ministry is conducting a feasibility study on the creation of a
European armaments agency with a view to easing cross-border arms
procurement.
Other lessons learnt from civilian privatisation are also working their way
into the military. The introduction last year of a New Management Strategy
has led this year to the analysis of defence resources by budget-holder
rather than by programme.
The biggest budget-holder is UK Land Forces, which covers the armed forces
outside Germany, with Pounds 2bn to spend; followed by the Chief of Fleet
Support, which provides logistical support for the navy, with Pounds 1.6bn.
Those figures exclude equipment procurement.
The strategy, which introduced efficiency targets for planning and resource
allocations, is designed to save 1.5 per cent of the defence budget in its
first year, with a target of 2.5 per cent savings in each of the next three
years. Such measures should save up to Pounds 4bn annually within three
years, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, said yesterday.
The ministry has also begun a period of 'simulated trading' with the Defence
Research Agency, which it hopes will lead to the agency, which consists of
four military research establishments, becoming a trading fund from April
next year. Trading-fund status would allow it to retain some of the revenues
it generates.
A total of 11 agencies, such as the Defence Research Agency and the
Meteorological Office, each now has its own chief executive, who is
'personally accountable for the efficient and effective management of the
activities under their control'. The chief executives will also be
responsible for compliance with the Citizen's Charter.
The white paper also outlines plans for the ministry to subsidise personnel
who want to buy property. Several other initiatives including ventures with
housing associations are planned.
The white paper contains precise numbers of equipment for the first time.
For exam-ple, the number of advanced medium-range air-to-air missiles to be
bought for the Royal Navy's Sea Harrier jump jets is 210, with 100 heavy
Spearfish torpedoes. However some figures, such as the number of Sting Ray
lightweight torpedoes, remain classified.
The ministry has set up an environmental task force under Lord Cranborne to
ensure compliance with international protocols on ozone-layer depletion.
Studies are under way into the feasibility of employing women in the
infantry, the Royal Marines commando forces and the Royal Armoured Corps.
But Mr Archie Hamilton, armed forces minister, said there was a 'certain
reluctance' about seeing women in the front line.
He said: 'We are looking right across the board and investigating what roles
women should take, but it is unlikely that the recommendation will be that
they can go to the infantry.'
</TEXT>
