<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Irish MPs told of coup at Telecom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Brendan Hynes was sacked as chairman of Telecom Eireann, the state-run
telecommunications company, at the weekend because he had lost the support
and confidence of its board of directors, Ms Maire Geoghegan Quinn, the
Irish minister for transport and telecommunications, said yesterday.
She told parliament that she was left with a choice of either firing Mr
Hynes or facing the resignation 'individually or collectively' of the board.
'The problem was not with the former chairman's thinking. The problem was
with (his) modus operandi . . . the chairman must secure board approval for
his/her proposals,' she said.
The opposition Fine Gael party attacked the government for 'mismanaging'
what is Ireland's most profitable public sector company and a party
spokesman said: 'We are not really any wiser over the reasons for the
differences between Mr Hynes and the board.' Telecom made a IPounds 94m
profit on a IPounds 782m turnover last year. It has 1m customers, 13,500
employees and is estimated to be worth some IPounds 1bn were it to be
privatised.
Mr Hynes was appointed to the post just six months ago, replacing Mr Michael
Smurfit who resigned last September over a controversial deal to build a new
headquarters.
Mr Hynes took a hands-on approach to the non-executive chairmanship,
believing he had been given a mandate from the then telecommunications
minister, Mr Seamus Brennan, to carry out a thorough review of the company
ahead of its possible privatisation. Mr Brennan, however, lost his post to
Ms Geoghegan Quinn, in the cabinet reshuffle following the resignation of Mr
Charles Haughey as prime minister.
Nonetheless, Mr Hynes, whose main business experience has been in the mining
and exploration sector, pressed ahead with his review and in a statement at
the weekend indicated that despite Telecom's good profit levels, problems of
overmanning and heavy capital expenditure plans would have to be addressed
to make the company competitive in the single European market.
Telecom's directors yesterday went on the counter-attack saying that they
'unanimously' reject Mr Hynes' criticisms and that on June 26 they passed a
motion of no confidence in him as chairman.
Observer, page 21
</TEXT>
