<DATE>920708
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / G7 'would back aid with force': Western leaders condemn
warring factions in former Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH, HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN leaders warned the warring sides in Bosnia-Hercegovina yesterday
that they would be prepared to use military force to ensure humanitarian aid
reached Sarajevo, the republic's capital, if the international airlift is
endangered.
In one of the most outspoken statements on the crisis in the former
Yugoslavia by any international forum, the leaders of the Group of Seven
industrialised nations condemned those responsible for the violence. They
said the Serbian leadership and the Serb-dominated Yugoslav army bore the
greatest responsibility.
The declaration came as shooting, including tank rounds, broke out in
Sarajevo in the worst fighting since a partial ceasefire was agreed last
month.
After appealing to all parties in Bosnia not to imperil the humanitarian
effort or endanger the lives of those engaged in the relief operation, the
G7 leaders said: 'Should these efforts fail due to an unwillingness of those
concerned to fully co-operate with the United Nations, we believe the
Security Council will have to consider other measures, not excluding
military means, to achieve its humanitarian objectives.'
The special declaration on Yugoslavia made clear the Sarajevo airlift could
only be the beginning of a larger humanitarian effort and the transport of
aid by road to Sarajevo, and other needy parts of Bosnia-Hercegovina, must
also be guaranteed.
Although all subscribed to the declaration, the G7 members differ in their
willingness to contemplate the use of force. France is in the forefront of
those believing a military effort will eventually be required, and President
Francois Mitterrand has been putting forward various ideas on how it could
be organised.
One is that a combined force of troops from the UN and the nine-nation
Western European Union should ensure the safety of aid convoys, operating
under a new mandate of the UN Security Council. An ad hoc group of WEU
officials has been considering contingency plans for operations in the
former Yugoslavia and a special meeting of WEU foreign ministers is due to
discuss the situation in the margin of the summit of the Conference on
Security and Co-operation starting in Helsinki tomorrow.
The US has been much more circumspect. Mr James Baker, US secretary of
state, said it was obvious that humanitarian supplies had to go in by land
as well as air, but stressed it was 'unlikely' the US would send in ground
forces to provide protection for trucks.
While the US has made clear it is prepared to use military aircraft and
naval ships to ensure the safety of the aid airlift and any future land
convoys, it would leave the provision of ground forces to 'other countries',
according to General Brent Scowcroft, President George Bush's national
security adviser.
Britain has been 'at the cautious end of the spectrum', in the words of Mr
Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary.
But even Mr Hurd, while ruling out the use of British ground troops, was
forced to admit that the humanitarian aid airlift was a 'risky and
dangerous' operation.
However, British officials, like their American counterparts, consider there
are enough other countries which would volunteer to provide ground forces.
The declaration raised the prospect of transforming the European Community's
peace conference chaired by Lord Carrington into a wider international
conference under joint EC-UN auspices.
Lord Carrington will fly to New York this week in line with the G7's desire
that there should be consultations between the EC conference, the UN and the
other parties concerned with the Yugoslav crisis. Mr Hurd, in his role as
president of the EC Council of Ministers, will visit Sarajevo, Belgrade,
Zagreb, Ljubljana, Tirana the Albanian capital, and Skopje, the capital of
Macedonia, next week.
Judy Dempsey in Helsinki adds: Russia is continuing to oppose moves to
exclude the new rump state of Yugoslavia - consisting just of Serbia and
Montenegro - from the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe.
As leaders of CSCE states start arriving in Helsinki today for a meeting,
they are likely to find themselves in a serious dispute about how to treat
Yugoslavia.
While Russia wants the Serb-dominated Yugoslavia to remain in the CSCE,
several western countries are insisting that it be banned.
